INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '64ac039b-b20e-40de-bfcb-9a6721d938c4',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jupyter + Pandas — Interactive DataFrame Exploration You Can't Do in Scripts$escape$,
  $escape$Jupyter turns Pandas from a data library into a visual workbench. Every DataFrame expression in a cell auto-renders as an HTML table — no print() needed. Use df.head(), df.describe(), and df.info() in separate cells to iteratively profile data without rerunning your pipeline.

GroupBy results shine in notebooks: df.groupby('category')['revenue'].agg(['mean', 'sum']) renders instantly as a formatted table you can eyeball for anomalies. Chain .plot() on any aggregation and the chart appears inline.

Merge debugging is where Jupyter saves hours. Run the merge in one cell, then validate with df_merged.isna().sum() in the next to catch join mismatches immediately. Use pd.merge(left, right, on='key', how='left', indicator=True) and filter on _merge to see unmatched rows live.

Pro tip: Jupyter's last-expression display means you can end any cell with a Series or DataFrame slice — df.loc[df['score'] > 90, ['name', 'score']] — and get a rich table without wrapping it in display().$escape$,
  $escape$import pandas as pd

# In Cell 1: Load and preview
df = pd.read_csv('sales.csv')
df.head(10)  # Jupyter renders as HTML table

# In Cell 2: GroupBy with inline plot
df.groupby('region')['revenue'].sum().plot(kind='bar', title='Revenue by Region')

# In Cell 3: Merge and validate join quality
orders = pd.read_csv('orders.csv')
merged = pd.merge(df, orders, on='customer_id', how='left', indicator=True)
merged['_merge'].value_counts()  # Spot unmatched rows instantly$escape$,
