INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '69a00a18-7770-4f82-acaf-c65a802bbd58',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jupyter Feature Engineering — Interactive Encoding, Scaling & Binning in One Notebook$escape$,
  $escape$Jupyter's cell-by-cell execution makes feature engineering iterative and visual. Build your pipeline incrementally: encode categoricals in one cell, inspect value distributions with .value_counts() inline, then scale numerics in the next. The key advantage is immediate feedback — call df.head() after each transform to catch issues before they propagate.

Use pandas + scikit-learn together. OrdinalEncoder for ordinal cats, OneHotEncoder (via pd.get_dummies) for nominals. For scaling, StandardScaler or MinMaxScaler fit in one cell, transform in the next — keeping fitted objects in memory across cells. Binning with pd.cut() or pd.qcut() lets you visualize bin distributions instantly with df['binned'].hist() rendered inline.

Interaction features multiply or combine columns — create them, then use Jupyter's built-in display to render correlation heatmaps (sns.heatmap(df.corr())) without leaving the notebook. This tight feedback loop between transform and visualization is what makes Jupyter the default environment for feature engineering workflows.$escape$,
  $escape$import pandas as pd
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Encode categoricals inline — inspect immediately
df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['category'], drop_first=True)
df.head()  # Jupyter renders this as a rich HTML table

# Scale numerics, keep scaler in memory for later cells
scaler = StandardScaler()
df[['price', 'quantity']] = scaler.fit_transform(df[['price', 'quantity']])

# Bin continuous feature and visualize distribution inline
df['price_bin'] = pd.qcut(df['price'], q=4, labels=['low','mid','high','top'])
df['price_bin'].value_counts().plot.bar()  # renders inline with %matplotlib inline

# Interaction feature + instant correlation check
df['price_x_qty'] = df['price'] * df['quantity']$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
