INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f4bcddec-185e-4964-8f9e-61e3f95af9e3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jupyter Reproducibility — Seeds, Pinning, and Escaping Notebook Chaos$escape$,
  $escape$Jupyter notebooks are reproducibility nightmares by default. Out-of-order cell execution, hidden state, and unpinned dependencies make results impossible to replicate. Fix this systematically.

First, pin your entire environment. Use %pip install inside notebooks instead of !pip — it guarantees installation into the kernel's environment, not a random system Python. Export with !pip freeze > requirements.txt in a dedicated cell.

Second, seed everything in Cell 1. NumPy, random, and framework-specific RNGs all need explicit seeds. Use a single SEED constant and propagate it.

Third, eliminate hidden state. Restart Kernel & Run All before every commit. If it fails, your notebook has order-dependent bugs. The %reset magic clears the namespace for targeted debugging.

Finally, convert to scripts for production. jupyter nbconvert --to script strips markdown and cell metadata, producing a linear .py file. Pair this with papermill for parameterized, headless execution — it runs notebooks as functions with injected parameters and captures output cells as artifacts.$escape$,
  $escape$# Cell 1 — Reproducibility preamble
import random, numpy as np

SEED = 42
random.seed(SEED)
np.random.seed(SEED)

# Pin deps to kernel's env (not !pip)
%pip install pandas==2.2.2 scikit-learn==1.5.1 --quiet

# Convert notebook to script from terminal:
# jupyter nbconvert --to script analysis.ipynb

# Run headless with parameters:
# papermill analysis.ipynb output.ipynb -p SEED 123$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
